Premise Energy Usage Clustering (Disaggregation) and Load Forecasting

Using the TSrepr package to do the time series transformations and PAM for k-mediod clustering. Forecasting is TBD. Performs clustering of time series, across consumers/premises and, thus, groups premises into similar usage patterns (i.e. cluster assignments). By clustering of consumers of electricity load, we can extract typical load profiles across consumers, improve the accuracy of consequent electricity consumption forecasting, detect anomalies or monitor a whole smart grid.

Helper functions for using the TSRepr library

## write my own transformation functions
to_znorm <- function(x) {
  mu <- mean(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  sigma <- sd(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  zscore <- (x-mu)/sigma
  return(list(zscore=zscore, mu=mu, sigma=sigma))
}

from_znorm <- function(x, mu, sigma) {
  return(x*sigma+mu)
}

## original repr_matrix() takes a matrix of time series data with each row being 
## the time series vector (i.e. each row is hourly energy usage per premise)
## function to mimic repr_matrix() but with a list of usage by premise
## returns a tibble with usage in columns and each row being a distinct premise
repr_matrix2 <- function(x, ts_fun, args, norm_fun) {
  x <- as_tibble(x)
  
  b <- lapply(split(x, f=factor(x[[1]])), function(y) y$kw)
  bnormed <- lapply(b, norm_fun)
  
  bseas <- lapply(bnormed, function(x, ts_fun, args) { 
    x <- x[[1]]
    do.call(ts_fun, c(list(x=x), args)) 
    }, ts_fun=ts_fun, args=args)
  
  b1 <- t(bind_rows(bseas))
  colnames(b1) <- paste0("V", 1:ncol(b1))
  #premise_nums <- rownames(b1)

  return(list(mat=as_tibble(b1),
              mu=sapply(bnormed, function(x) x$mu),
              sigma=sapply(bnormed, function(x) x$sigma)))
}

Perform aggregation and clustering (via TSRepr and PAM)

##
pnums <- as.character(unique(usage$prem_num))
print(pnums)

## 
## freq is based on data points so there are 60 minutes in 1 hour and 24 hours in a day
z_orig <- repr_matrix2(x=usage, 
                       ts_fun=repr_seas_profile, 
                       args=list(freq=24, func=mean), 
                       norm_fun=to_znorm)

z <- z_orig$mat
z_mu <- z_orig$mu
z_sigma <- z_orig$sigma
dim(z)
z

## PAM ... k-mediods
clusterings <- lapply(c(2:5), function(x) pam(z, x))

## internal validation index is have to be used to determine an optimal number of clusters. 
## I will use well known Davies-Bouldin index for this evaluation. By Davies-Bouldin 
## index computation, we want to find a minimum of its values.
DB_values <- sapply(seq_along(clusterings), function(x) 
                  intCriteria(as.matrix(z), as.integer(clusterings[[x]]$clustering),
                              c("Davies_Bouldin")))

# lowest number for most methods, but FleaClip is the biggest delta/change
DB_idx <- tibble(clusters=c(2:5), DBindex=unlist(DB_values)) 
DB_idx %>%
  ggplot(aes(clusters, DBindex)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw()

cluster_num <- DB_idx[order(DB_idx$DBindex),][["clusters"]][1] #-1

# prepare data for plotting
# with reduced dataset melt (gather) across variables and normalized values plus PAM classes
# and then adds time (index) and a unique ID (could do that from data frame with gather)
z_plot <- z %>%
  mutate(class=as.factor(clusterings[[cluster_num]]$clustering)) %>%
  gather(variable, value, 1:(ncol(z))) %>%
  mutate(Time=rep(1:ncol(z), each=nrow(z)),
         ID=rep(1:nrow(z), ncol(z)),
         variable=as_factor(variable))

# prepare medoids
centers <- clusterings[[cluster_num]]$medoids %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  rowid_to_column(var="ID") %>%
  mutate(class=ID) %>%
  gather(variable, value, contains("V")) %>% # need to fix the contains to work generally
  mutate(Time=as.integer(as_factor(variable)))
